Explanation
1. The Good: Strandedness is Perfect
expected_format": "ISR": Your library is Stranded-Reverse (very common for Illumina TruSeq Stranded kits).
compatible_fragment_ratio": 1.0: This is perfect. It means 100% of the fragments Salmon could map matched the expected strand. Salmon is not "losing" any data due to strand settings.
2. The Interesting: Why is Mapping ~49%?
Look at these two lines:
num_frags_with_concordant_consistent_mappings": 10,339,129 (These are "perfect" pairs)
num_frags_with_inconsistent_or_orphan_mappings": 8,192,220 (These are "orphans" or "discordant" pairs)
The Interpretation:
You have about 8 million fragments where only one side of the pair (R1 or R2) mapped well, or they mapped to different genes, or they were too far apart. In bacteria, this often happens because:
Operon Structure: Reads might span across two different genes in the same operon, confusing the "paired-end" logic.
Fragment Length: If your library had many very short fragments, the R1 and R2 might overlap or be "discordant."

